metadata.title: Beechcraft Bonanza
aws::graph::propositions: # Beechcraft Bonanza V-tail Safety and Structural Issues
Most V-tail failures in the Beechcraft Bonanza involved flight under visual flight rules into instrument meteorological conditions.
Most V-tail failures in the Beechcraft Bonanza involved flight into thunderstorms.
Most V-tail failures in the Beechcraft Bonanza involved airframe icing.
The Beechcraft Bonanza 35 has a relatively narrow center of gravity envelope.
The V-tail design of the Beechcraft Bonanza 35 is intolerant of imbalances.
Imbalances in the Beechcraft Bonanza 35 tail can be caused by damage.
Imbalances in the Beechcraft Bonanza 35 tail can be caused by improper maintenance.
Imbalances in the Beechcraft Bonanza 35 tail can be caused by repainting.
Imbalances in the Beechcraft Bonanza 35 tail may induce dangerous aeroelastic flutter.
The V-tail ruddervator skins of the Beechcraft Bonanza are made of magnesium.
The magnesium used in the Beechcraft Bonanza V-tail ruddervator skins has anodic properties.
The magnesium ruddervator skins of the Beechcraft Bonanza tend to corrode.
Corrosion of the V-tail ruddervator skins often results in permanent grounding of affected Beechcraft Bonanza aircraft.
The corrosion problem in Beechcraft Bonanza V-tail ruddervator skins can only be fixed by complete replacement of the skins or the entire empennage.
The required parts for fixing the Beechcraft Bonanza V-tail ruddervator skins are no longer available.
The American Bonanza Society has issued a reward of $500,000.
The American Bonanza Society's reward is to encourage the development of aftermarket replacement skins under a supplemental type certificate.
Many Beechcraft Bonanza 35 owners insist that the aircraft is reasonably safe.
The reputation of the Beechcraft Bonanza 35 has resulted in reduced purchase costs for budget-conscious buyers.

text:
Most V-tail failures involved flight under visual flight rules into instrument meteorological conditions, flight into thunderstorms, or airframe icing.
In addition to the structural issues, the Bonanza 35 has a relatively narrow center of gravity envelope, and the tail design is intolerant of imbalances caused by damage, improper maintenance, or repainting. Such imbalances may induce dangerous aeroelastic flutter. Due to the anodic properties of the magnesium used for the V-tail ruddervator skins, they tend to corrode, often resulting in permanent grounding of affected aircraft because the problem can only be fixed by complete replacement of the skins or the entire empennage, and the required parts are no longer available. The American Bonanza Society has issued a reward of $500,000 to encourage the development of aftermarket replacement skins under a supplemental type certificate. Despite these issues, many Bonanza 35 owners insist that the aircraft is reasonably safe, and its reputation has resulted in reduced purchase costs for budget-conscious buyers.
